Slide 12: Traffic gradient sites in the snapshot data

Plot the example of traffic gradient sites as an example of a single grouping variable in the snapshot data

#-----Snapshot data setup-----

# The goal is to create a fall dataset for the variance components that
# identifies the gradient sites by keeping all observations that have more than
# 3 observations for the group_loc variable.  Note:  `fvc` is a tibble.  In the
# VCA package below it needs to be converted to a data frame.


fvc <- snapshot %>%
    filter(season == 2)  %>%
    group_by(group_loc) %>%
    mutate(count = n()) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    filter(count > 3) %>%
    select(-count)
#-----dotplot of fvc-----

ggplot(fvc, aes(x = group_loc, y = ln_nox)) +
    geom_boxplot(aes(x=group_loc, group = group_loc),
                 outlier.color = NA, 
                 width = .6) +
    geom_dotplot(aes(group = group_loc), binaxis = "y", binwidth = .01,
                 stackdir =  "center", color = "red", fill = NA, dotsize = 2) +
        labs(title = "Boxplots with Overlaid Dotplots\nfor Ln(NOx) in Fall by Gradient Site Index",
         y = "ln(NOx) in ln(ppb)",
         x = "Gradient Site Index") + 
    theme_bw()

Slide 18: Snapshot data stratified by gradient site

#-----tidyverse stratified summary snapshot-----

# One pipeline approach to coding this.  Note that since `vc_summary` is used
# later on, we need to filter out the "Total" row below
vc_summary <- fvc %>%
    group_by(group_loc) %>%
    summarise(N = n(),
              mean = mean(ln_nox),
              sd = sd(ln_nox)) %>%
    mutate(group_loc = as.character(group_loc) ) %>%
    bind_rows(fvc %>% summarise(group_loc = "Total",
                                N = n(),
                                mean = mean(ln_nox),
                                sd = sd(ln_nox) ) ) %>%
    mutate_if(is.double, round, 3)

Slide 19: Assessing between and within site variability

#-----gradient variability-----

# create variance table after omitting the total row
vc_var <- vc_summary %>% filter(N < 100) %>%
    summarise(N_sites = n(),
              median_grand = median(mean),
              mean_grand = mean(mean),
              median_sd = median(sd), 
              within_sd = sqrt(mean(sd^2)),
              between_sd = sd(mean)
              ) %>% 
    mutate_if(is.double, round, 3)

# show table
vc_var

Slide 21 + 22: Variance components with VCA

VCA allows the MOM estimates and easy comparison with REML estimates of variance components.

#-----VCA implementation-----

# tibble, so we've made that adjustment in the function arguments

# visualize data

# different ways to estimate variance components
fit_MOM <- anovaVCA(ln_nox ~ group_loc, Data = as.data.frame(fvc) )
fit_MOM

Slides 23 & 24: Estimation using lme

A key point here that the lmer REML estimates are the same as from VCA. Discuss why we use ML at all â basically to easily compare models. Because REML adjusts for the bias in estimation, we canât compare models fit with REML.

Slide 32: Mixed model with the Snapshot data: Pop_5000 as one fixed covariate

The following analyses address how the two variance components change when different covariates are in the model. As was done in the Peretz paper, think about whether we expect an impact on the variance components and whether the impact should affect the between site or within site variance estimates.

Note: Because one might want to do some model selection comparisons with these analyses, I used the ML option (i.e.Â REML = FALSE).

Note (not necessarily discussed in lecture): The fixed effect estimates will change when there is correlation between fixed and random effect parts of the model. Random effects do not address residual confounding. The most appropriate assumption is to assume the random effects are independent of the fixed effects. In the following example there appears to be some correlation between the D2Comm variable and the random effects, leading to a change in the coefficient estimate for D2Comm between the fixed and mixed models.

#-----mixed model vs lm: 2 covars-----

lmfit2 <- lm(ln_nox ~ Pop_5000 + D2Comm, data = fvc)

Slide 37: Regression for prediction with random effects

To predict from a mixed model, i.e.Â a linear model with fixed and random effects, you MUST have the same groups as you used to fit your model. You canât predict on new groups. Thus random effects models are less commonly used in prediction problems than other kinds of variance models (e.g.Â geostatistical models).

When you predict from a mixed model, you need to decide whether you want to only predict the fixed effects, or incorporate the random effects into the predictions.

The following shows full predictions (fixed+random) and then fixed effect only predictions in the snapshot gradient site data for the mixed effect model with only one covariate:

#-----mixed effects model prediction on same data-----

# Prediction incorporating fixed & random effects
p0 <- predict(mixedfit1_REML)
plot(fvc$group_loc,p0)

# Predictions of fixed effects only
# The re.form = NA option omits random effects
p1 <- predict(mixedfit1_REML, re.form = NA)
plot(fvc$group_loc,p1)

identical(p0,p1)
[1] FALSE
plot(p1,p0)

# Note the predictions with random effects are more variable, as one would expect.
summary(p1)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
  3.903   4.131   4.232   4.267   4.441   4.700 
summary(p0)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
  3.670   4.021   4.336   4.266   4.532   4.722

When you predict in a new dataset from a mixed model, you MUST have all grouping variables and random effects used in the model fitting. However, if you donât want to predict at all groups, you can set their values to NA. For details, see this predict.merMod help page.

For example, to predict at one location per gradient site in the snapshot data:

#-----mixed effects model prediction on new data-----

newdata <- with(fvc, expand.grid(Pop_5000=unique(Pop_5000), 
                                 group_loc=unique(group_loc)))
dim(newdata)
[1] 3128    2
# new data, all RE
p2 <- predict(mixedfit1_REML, newdata)

# new data, level 0 (fixed effects only)
p3 <- predict(mixedfit1_REML, newdata, re.form = NA)

# explicitly specify RE model we want
p4 <- predict(mixedfit1_REML, newdata, re.form = ~(1|group_loc)) 

# verify that p2 and p4 are identical as they are supposed to be
identical(p2, p4)
[1] TRUE
plot(p3, p2)

# Note the predictions with random effects are more variable, as one would expect.
summary(p3)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
  3.903   4.131   4.232   4.267   4.441   4.700 
summary(p2)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
  3.486   4.078   4.251   4.267   4.466   5.149

#-----tidyverse stratified summary snapshot-----

# One pipeline approach to coding this.  Note that since
# `vc_summary` is used later on, we need to filter out the
# 'Total' row below
vc_summary <- fvc %>%
    group_by(group_loc) %>%
    summarise(N = n(), mean = mean(ln_nox), sd = sd(ln_nox)) %>%
    mutate(group_loc = as.character(group_loc)) %>%
    bind_rows(fvc %>%
        summarise(group_loc = "Total", N = n(), mean = mean(ln_nox),
            sd = sd(ln_nox))) %>%
    mutate_if(is.double, round, 3)

# we already rounded
